Tutorial: transPACT¶

transPACT stands for trans-AT PKS Annotation and Comparison Tool. Two applications are supported by the transPACT platform:

  • The prediction of the substrate specificity of KS sequences
    As KS domains rule the specificity of the incorporated substrates in trans-AT assembly lines, the automated prediction of KS specicifities represents a major driver in the discovery of polyketide structure.

  • The identification of conserved modules blocks among the PKSs under study
    The transPACT comparison tool generates a dendrogram representation, illustrating the similarity relationships between the PKSs under study.

Figure 1: Workflow of the transPACT software. (A) Phylogenetic placement of KS sequences to a reference phylogeny in order to predict their substrate activities. (B) Phylogenetic comparison of the PKSs sharing module or domain blocks using network and dendrogram representations.
Figure reprinted and adapted from Helfrich et al., 2021.


The transPACT software is embedded in a Linux platform due to package dependecies. It was developed in Python 2.7. Currently, transPACT is available in a super computer environment or in MacOS (mounted with an Ubuntu Virtual Machine - Oracle VirtualBox).

Tutorial: set-up a VSC environment¶

1. Getting access¶

First, you should request a VSC accounts and sufficient credits. If you already have a VSC account, you can skip this step.

Generate a public and a private key: https://docs.vscentrum.be/en/latest/access/getting_access.html#create-a-public-private-key-pair

Request a VSC account: https://docs.vscentrum.be/en/latest/access/getting_access.html#apply-for-account

Log-in to a cluster:

  • Windows - PuTTY is recommended
  • MacOS
  • Linux

Credits:

  • Introductory credits are granted by sending a kindly mail to hpcinfo@icts.kuleuven.be (mention that you are new to the HPC)
  • 2000 credits (value of 7)
  • Valid for 6 months
  • Expired? Ask friendly for an extension

VSC User Documention: https://docs.vscentrum.be/en/latest/

2. Set-up miniconda3¶

In order to manage virtual environments and python package, the conda python package manager is required.
A full tutorial is provided in the VSC documentation: https://docs.vscentrum.be/en/latest/software/python_package_management.html?highlight=conda

A short version of the aforementioned tutorial is provided below.

In [ ]:
#download miniconda
wget https://repo.continuum.io/miniconda/Miniconda3-latest-Linux-x86_64.sh
In [ ]:
#execute the miniconda3 bash script and extract it in your data directory
bash Miniconda3-latest-Linux-x86_64.sh -b -p $VSC_DATA/miniconda3
In [ ]:
#add miniconda3 to your path
#do this within your $VSC_DATA folder
export PATH="${VSC_DATA}/miniconda3/bin:${PATH}"
In [ ]:
#if miniconda3 has been correctly installed and referenced to your path, it prints conda's path
which conda

If adding conda is causing problems, removing your path may be an option (but be careful with this option as it may have consequences on other softwares).

In [ ]:
#Only run it with the $VSC_DATA folder!
#to reinitialize your path and add miniconda3 to it: 
export PATH = 
export PATH=${PATH%:/miniconda3/bin}
export PATH=${PATH/'/miniconda3'/}

#to search for miniconda3 and add it to path
export PATH="$( echo $PATH| tr : '\n' |grep -v miniconda3 | paste -s -d: )"

Tutorial: running transPACT on a Linux terminal¶

The transPACT software requires Python, Perl and two others modules. In tbe present section, a line-by-line tutorial is outlined.

Figure 2: Overview of the files system of transPACT.

(A) Alignment and extraction of the KS numbers
(B) KS substrate specificity annotation
(C) Generation of an all vs. all table with DIAMOND
(D) Processing of the annotation file
(E) Dendrogram PKS comparison




0. Create a virtual environment with conda with the required packages¶

It applies for both the VSC and Ubuntu environments.

In [ ]:
#cloning the transPACT github repository 
git clone https://github.com/AntoineRuzy/transPACT_BDE
In [ ]:
#go into the newly created directory
cd transPACT
In [ ]:
#create the environment with all the package dependencies listed in the text file
conda create --name transPACT --file conda_packages.txt
In [ ]:
#configurate the shell to use the conda commands - NEED TO RESTART YOUR SESSION AFTER RUNNING THIS COMMAND
conda init bash
In [ ]:
#activate the environment
conda activate transPACT

Conda commands cheat sheet: https://docs.conda.io/projects/conda/en/4.6.0/_downloads/52a95608c49671267e40c689e0bc00ca/conda-cheatsheet.pdf




1. Alignment, extraction of KS numbers and creation of DIAMOND table¶

First, the 647 KS sequences of reference need to be combined with the query KS sequences in a single FASTA file. It should be noted that a python script is included to transform an aligned FASTA file into an unaligned FASTA file i.e. removing the gaps.

In [ ]:
#concatenate two files
#be careful that there should not be an empty line of the end of each concatenated files
cat file1.fasta file2.fasta > file3.fasta

Once you have a single FASTA file, the headers of the KS sequences should be modified in order to fit in the following naming format:

> <PKS name>|<KS number>
AIIGISCHVPGAQDHHYFWQNLLNGHESVALLSAEELAAAGIAEELRQNPNYVPARLTIEDKDCFDPAFFNISPRNAAYMDPQARLLLLHSWKAMEDA
GLAVGDTPETGVFMSATTNFYQLPLGLPVHALQGADGHAAGIQAQGGMIPNTISYHLGLKGPSMFVQSLCSSSLVGLKLACQSLQAGEAKMALIGGA
NLFAFSRVGHLYEPEMNLSDDGHCRTFDAAATGVVEGEGVCVIVLKKALDAVADRDHIYALLRGISLNNDGADKAGFHAPGVKGQAAAARAVLTATG
VDPTTIRYVEAHGTGTPSGDAIEVAALSEAYPNGTHRCAIGSLKPNIGNLDTAGGLAGVIKVALGLYHGAIPPQINFNEPAPDIDFTDSPFYVPTQAE
PWQDDKAPRRAAQNHYSLGGTNVHAIYEA

In [ ]:
#extract KS numbers from initial names and format the FASTA headers 
python adaptKS_fastaNames.py #remember to modify the path within the file with nano

If the file returns an error, it is very likely that the initial encoding of names was not correct. To check the names that do not contain a correct formatting of the KS numbers, run the following command:

In [ ]:
grep -v -E '(_(KS)[0-9]{1,2}_)' annotation_ar_20220331.tsv

VSC implementation

If you are using a VSC implementation, the below explanations can be followed.

In a typical context, one would possess the sequences of the KS domains of interest stored in a fasta file. Thus, you need to align the query sequences to the reference sequences. To do so, we recommend using MUSCLE.

In order to run a job on the VSC, you need to create a .pbs file and send it to the queue. Please refer to this tutorial to understand how to submit a job.
Create a file named muscle_run.pbs containing the following lines and then submit your job using the qsub command. It should be noted that, by the way, the all vs. all DIAMOND table is generated using the same job script.

In [ ]:
#!/usr/bin/env bash

#PBS -l nodes=1:ppn=36
#PBS -l walltime=00:10:00
#PBS -l pmem=5gb
#PBS -A default_project
#PBS -N alignment_full

#modify your path
cd /vsc-hard-mounts/leuven-data/339/vsc33918/transPACT/data/dendogram_test

#load modules
module purge
module load MUSCLE/3.8.31-foss-2018a
module load DIAMOND/0.9.24-foss-2018a

#run muscle to align sequences
#run diamond to create an all vs. all table
clear

#modify the path of the files
muscle -in full_sequences_renamed.fasta -out full_sequences_aln.fasta -maxiters 2
diamond makedb -d all --in full_sequences_aln.fasta
ls

Non-VSC implementation

If you are not using the VSC, the FASTA file can be aligned using any multiple sequence aligner e.g. MUSCLE on EMBL.
The all vs. all DIAMOND table can be generated using the aforementioned command lines. However, DIAMOND first needs to be installed.




2. Assign functional clade to trans-AT PKS's KS domains¶

INPUT: FASTA file with KS sequences and their corresponding standardized names.
OUTPUT: Tab-separated text file with names, clade number and clade description.

In [ ]:
#run for the single KS domain as an example
#STDOUT (ouput within the console)
python2 transPACT_substrate_from_faa.py example/test.faa

#RECOMMENDED: OUTPUT TO FILE (to save results, needed for further steps)
python2 transPACT_substrate_from_faa.py example/test.faa > clade_annotation.txt




3. Generate dendrogram visualization for comparison¶

INPUT: Tab-separated text file in a wide data format with KS numbers as columns, PKS names as rows and substrate annotations as values; FASTA file containing the KS sequences
OUTPUT: Newick tree file encoding the dendrogram representation ; ITOL annotation file

Suggested weights for distance calculation are JI = 0, DSS = 0.32, AI = 0.68, the same weights that are used in BiG-SCAPE's distance calculation for trans-AT PKS pathways. [from the transPACT GitHub]

Set up¶

In [ ]:
#create a dedicated directory
mkdir data/dendrogram_test && cd data/dendrogram_test
In [ ]:
#copy the python script into that directory
cp ../code/generate_dendrogram_userweights.py ./
In [ ]:
#list of scripts mandatory to have in your dendrogram folder

annotation2clades.py
cladetsv2tbl.pl
generate_dendrogram_userweights.py
generate_itol.pl
647KS_ar_20220331.fasta
adapt_fastaNames.py

#use the cp command or FileZilla

If the permission to copy is denied, it is recommended to use the FileZilla application to move document within your file system and between your local system and the VSC server.

Processing of the annotation file¶

Generate clades.tsv file

You start with a file containing the clade annotation in the following format. Such a file can be generated using the transPACT_substrate_from_faa.py python script (see Section 2).

#Leaf_name Clade_name Clade_desc
GO485_KS11_00205 Clade_66 double_bonds
GO485_KS12_00205 Clade_31 eDB
GO485_KS13_00210 Clade_5 shifted_double_bonds
GO485_KS1_00250 Clade_2 amino acids
GO485_KS2_00250 Clade_62 eDB

Note the standardized names!

To extract the KS sequence names, the KS numbers and the clade numbers, the following python script has been developed (accesible on the aforementioned repository).

In [ ]:
python2 annotation2clades.py
#this script creates two files: full_annotation.tsv and full_annotation.clades.tsv

Generate annotation.tsv file

In [ ]:
perl cladetsv2tbl.pl > file.annotationtable.tsv
#change the path of the clades.tsv file in the perl script (use the nano command)
#Use the perl script from the dendrogram20190514 directory, it is the correct one

If you see a special character (namely ^M ) called the carriage return in the annotationtable.tsv file, then run the following command to get rid of it:

In [ ]:
sed -i -e "s/\r//g" file.annotationtable.tsv #it overwrites the file

Generate the Newick tree file¶

In [ ]:
#use nano to modify the path of the input files: annotation.tsv and full.dbp at line 576
nano generate_dendrogram_userweights.py
In [ ]:
#run the python script with the weights used in distance calculation
python2 generate_dendrogram_userweights.py 0 0.32 0.68

The .nwkcan then be uploaded on ITOL for visualization.

Generate ITOL annotation file¶

In order to generate an ITOL annotation file for KS domains, you will need three files and a Perl script:

  • an annotationtable.tsv file: clade assignment per KS domain for each PKS
  • a full clade annotation text file: clade assignment with its description for each KS domains
  • a upgma.nwk file: dendrogram architecture of the KS sequences
  • a perl script available at data/dendrogram20200320/generate_itol.pl
In [ ]:
perl generate_itol.pl > annotation_dom.txt

The annotation_dom.txt can then be added as an annotation file in ITOL alongside with the .nwk tree file.

Note that ITOL annotation file is of the following structure:

PKS,TOTAL LENGTH, EL|START|END|COLOR#|CLADE NUMBER, EL|...

4. Genome mining approach - phylogenetic assessment of the KS sequences of publicly available PKS's¶

ETL: Extract, Transform and Load

The latest version (29/03/2022) of the antismash clusterblast database is available through the following link: https://dl.secondarymetabolites.org/releases/clusterblast/clusterblast_20201113.tar.xz

It loads a .tar.xz file. Transfer that file on your global transPACT directory on the VSC (using FileZilla e.g.). To extract such a file, apply the following commands:

In [ ]:
tar xvzf clusterblast_20201113.tar.xz C /home/user/destination
# -C option enables you to extract the content in a directory of your choice

In order to gather KS domain sequences, you can either manually copy paste their sequences from a data base (e.g. antismash > copy to clipboard) or you can extract the sequences of the KS domain from protein sequences. The second option is described in the following lines.

Profile Hidden Markov Models are probabilistic models used to predict protein domains as they capture position-specific information about how conserved each amino acid is in each column of the alignment.

Source: EMBL-EBI training

Practically, we use the extract_tKS.py python script developed by Marnix Medema, that implements the aforementioned probabilistic model.

Input files:

  • HMM profiled for KS sequences: PKS.hmm
  • HMM profiled for AT sequences: AT.hmm
  • Multiple Sequence Alignment of your protein sequences (.afa file)

Both .hmm files are available on the BDE GitHub (under genome_mining_approach folder).

Output file:

  • FASTA file of the extracted KS sequences

Before running the script, we need to load the HMMER module.

In [ ]:
module purge #good practices to purge before creating a module environment

module spider HMMER #to grab the actual version of the HMMER module to load
module load ... 

module save HMMER_env
#'module savelist' to check your saved environment

From the whole clusterblast database, the HMM profile model identified 17,027 trans-AT KS sequences (on the date of May 02, 2022). The next step is now to predict the substrate specific for each predicted KS modules. However, let's first assess the accuracy of the HMM profile model.

My idea to format the fasta file of the clusterblast database is to use the following metrics as unique IDs:

  • RefSeq ID: NZ_xxxx => unique ID for the bacterial species
  • PKS positional ID: cXXX_XXX => unique ID for the PKS
  • Module positional ID: XXX-XXX => unique ID for a module within the PKS
  • KS number: KSx => unique ID for a KS given a specific PKS

Thus, a combination of the RefSeq ID, the PKS positional ID and the module positional ID yields an unique identifier for each KS sequence. Its KS number will be added by default by the pattern search.













































































































Output illustration¶

Loading the Newick tree file and its corresponding domain file in ITOL sould yield the following cladograms, either in circular or rectangular representations.

Figure 3: Circular and rectangular cladogram representation of module blocks conservation in ITOL.
Colors represent classes of KS clades that correlate with polyketide motifs i.e. KS specificity for the incoming subrate.

Cladograms can be accessed via https://itol.embl.de/export/62205120139364271650624817.
